n222 pages of tax-saving sections. L\nsave time, trouble and money in\npreparing your 1957 returns.\nOpen Your Account and Receive rjjw\nYour Tax Guide by Mail...\nEnclosed is check for $lO or more to open a Savings Account\nwith Prudential. Please send my free copy of J. K. Laiscr's\nr 1957 Income Tax Guide with new account book. r sg g 111 imj[\n1 (If joint account give both namet) i\n|f\nii. Nama \u2014Yous vUit nt>d\nt\n1 J tl YC\nI. cordially invited.\nI\" Open 9 a.m. to i p.m.\nii' City Zone ItKlllttHMaMtlll State J Closed Saturdays. I\nyr ___________________________\njyftruMtal\nbuilding association\n1338 G Street, N. W STerling 3-8316\nmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmam\nperiod of comparative stability\nThat doesn\u2019t mean that price*\nare going to drop back to their\n1955 levels, Just that they mar\nstop trying to push a hole in\nthe roof.\nActually, a sudden and sub\nstantial drop In prices would\ncreate problems aa serious as*\ninflation.\nEconomists know that some\nprice increases must be accepted\nas inevitable. For Instance, if\na business wants to attract\nworkers to offer higher wage*\nthan those prevailing in settled\nareas, or a new Industry may\nihave to offer a better Interest\nrate on borrowed money than\nan older and more established\ncompany would have to pay.\nAnd factors that raise business\nexpense tend to raise the prices\nof the goods those businesses\nproduce.\n4,000 Trade Shows\nNEW YORK. Jan. 4 I/PV\nA 5 per cent Increase In the\nnumber of trade shows end\nexpositions held throughout\nthe country is expected in\n1959 Arthur .Bmadbeck, presi\ndent. Coliseum Exhibition\nCorp., operators of the New\nYork Coliseum, estimates 4.000\ntrade shows wfll be held dur\ning the year, 300 more then\n1957.\n'Prosperous Recession/\nEconomists' View of 'SB\nContinued from Pago P-1\nThey believe that moot Ameri\ncans. except for what they read\nin the newspapers, may be\nhardly awara of the mild re\ncession which showed up In\nofficial indexes in October.\nToUl Output May Dip\nAn estimate that total out\nput of goods and services may\ndtp in the spring by about 1\nper cent from the 1957 peak Is\naccepted by Sec re tan of Com\nmerce Weeks and hlt,n advisers\nto the White House.\nThis would be a drop of per\nhaps 95 billion from the record\nrate of roughly 9442 billion an\nnually reached in the final\nquarter of 1957.\nill still would leave the value\nof American output slightly\nabove the estimated 9439 bil\nlion total for all of 1957. This\nwas an Inflated total which\nrepresented mostly price in\ncreases instead of real gains in\noutput.\nThe slack in business. It Is\nestimated, may last through\nmidyear. Many Government\nmen predict summer will bring\nthe recovery. Others don\u2019t ex\npect it until fall.\nCross Currents Apparent\n\u2022*TT\u00bbt* will be a year of cross\ncurrents instead of trends,\nsaid one official\nHere are some of the cur\nrent* and the direction they\nare running:\nPersonal income: The 1959\ntotal should wind up ahead of\n1957.\nJobe: Unemployment will\nrise. The longer the slump, the\nhigher it is likely to go. Job\nlessness may exceed 4 million\nthla airing; some predict 5 mil\nlion. Secretary of Labor Mitch\nell says it will not be \u2019\u2019serious.\u201d\nProdart ion: Those econo\nmists who foresee a fairly\nstrong recovery in eecond-hslf\n1958 expect that total produc\ntion will approach a rate of\n$450 Mlllon annually by the end\nof the year, somewhat less than\ntwo per cent above the current;\nrate.\nCredit: The Federal Reserve\nBoard has eased the harness\non credit with actions calcu\niatefl to loosen the money sup\nply and lower the cost of bor\nrowing somewhat. Lower in\nterest rates in 1958 would help\nhousing and Industry.\nProfits: A profit squeeze Is\nindicated. Corporation earn- 1\nings slipped from au annual\nrat* of about 945.2 billion\u2014be-!\nfore taxes\u2014in last-quarter 1958\nto $42 billions In second-quarter\n1957. Though the reporting of\nprofit statistics is a slow proc\ness. Washington economists be\nlieve the earnings rate by now\nhas gone slightly lower and will\nslip some more in early 1958.\n.Sales: Consumer demand is\nexpected to remain strong, the J\ndollar volume of retail tales,\nover the full year, should run\nslightly ahead of 1957 If only\nbecause the price level is higher.\nCenatrwctiea: Construction is\none of the bright spots. This\nbiggest single Industry\u2014and\neasiest to predict\u2014will have a\nrecord 849.6 million year in 1958,\nby official estimate. Cost In\nflation helps pad that figure,\nbut even In terms of physical\nvolume the new year will be\nsecond only to 1955.\nHousing: Though housing Is\npart of the construction pic\nture. its evident upturn de\nserves special mention because\nof its Impact on the whole\nconsumer goods and appliance\nfield. New homes mean new\nrefrigerators, washing ma-\nle\nUtilities in the Limelight\nInvestor interest is turning once again to the traditionally\ndependable utility group. The January issue of our \u201cReview\nof Business and Financial Conditions\u201d analyzes salient fea\ntures of the industry in detail, discusses historical growth\npatterns, and selects promising utility stocks for current in\nvestment. This issue also includes\n\"A Look at 1958\"\na brief year-end report by our research staff on prospects\nfor business and the stock market in the coming year.\nFor your copy of this timely \"Review\", simply visit one at\nour offices, call, or write Department S-54\nHIRSCH CO.\n\u25a0oofifivi *mi irvci iirfiofiffi wmm ragr Csffifififdi\n1636 KYI STREET N.W., WASHINGTON 6\n(Ground Floor Facing Farrogut Square)\nTvlepheoe: NAtiml I-2S4S\nNew York\u2014Baltimore\u2014Miami Beach\u2014Polm Beoch\nLondon\u2014Genevo\u2014Amsterdom\u2014Correspondent: Havana\nOUR DIRECT WIRE FACILITIES CONNECT US WITH\nA national NETWORK OF regional WESTIIEIT HOI SES\nwith 106 offices in 102 cities in the United States JpA.\n\u25a0BsMeEsacw'\u2019\nyj\nThese wires enoble us 